n is broken, so I need to fix that. I also have to check `clawhub list` against actual install roots and see if the default install directory uses `cwd` skills or `CLAWHUB_WORKDIR`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Modifying the update process**\\n\\nI’m considering that maybe we don’t need to overcomplicate things. I should modify the script and the cron job for automatic updates. I might set it up to safely update skills managed by clawhub if they exist in `workspace/skills` and have no local changes. Options include using `clawhub update <name> --no-input` or `--force`. I need to decide if I should go with `--no-input` for safety or just `--force` to avoid prompts. I'll check if the CLI really supports no-input for single skills.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering cron tasks**\\n\\nI’m realizing that if the prompt pops up in a noninteractive cron job, it might hang. Using `yes | clawhub update <name>` could work, but it feels a bit hacky. Since I’m unsure, maybe it’s better to use `clawhub update <name> --force` for the scheduled task, but only if everything is exact. I just want to ensure that the update occurs smoothly without any prompts getting in the way.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering script updates**\\n\\nI think it might be easiest to edit `skill_update_check.py` to build a report summarizing the installed skills across roots. I can also add an optional flag for auto-updating eligible clawhub managed skills, classifying recommendations clearly. I’ll modify the cron job prompt to run this script with `--auto-update-safe` and include a concise summary. Since the cron uses a model to execute the script, I could change the jobs.json prompt text for clarity. I could enhance the script to provide a better summary too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Addressing skill installation issues**\\n\\nThe user pointed out that there are \\\"many skills installed locally\\\" but a check indicates they're not. This highlights a couple of problems: first, incorrect search roots are leading to a false \\\"未安装\\\" message. Second, the report task only mentions \\\"值得关注\\\" without applying safe updates, and the version check is incorrectly looking for the `clawhub` package instead of `openclaw`. I think I need to adjust the prompt in jobs.json to check the correct package version. I’ll also review the auto-update cron session if needed.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Improving script for updates**\\n\\nI'm thinking that if the script prints structured text properly, it could help the model summarize the results. It might also be beneficial to save the output in JSON format. I need to update the jobs.json prompt to run a specific Python script for the safe auto-update check and also ensure it scans actual skill roots. Additionally, I should classify the results into categories like `✅ 已自动更新` and `🔄 可更新但跳过`. Updating the OpenClaw version check to `npm show openclaw version` is crucial too. I might consider changing the schedule time as well, though I'm not sure if that's necessary.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering script functionality**\\n\\nI'm thinking that the script should combine the clawhub list and the local skill directories. However, the cron report probably only needs updates for the installed skills, not every built-in one. Still, I believe having separate sections could be beneficial for clarity in the report. It's about striking the right balance between comprehensiveness and relevance to ensure the report is useful while not overwhelming with unnecessary details.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Classifying skills for updates**\\n\\nI’m working on how to classify skills from ClawHub records. First, I need to detect the actual path and status of each skill. Then there are local-only skills that aren’t in the ClawHub list, and I should source those locally. For ClawHub-managed skills, I need to figure out safe updates, especially since they likely won't have a .git directory. I might compare hashes to identify local modifications. ClawHub's update command can help manage this process.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting local skill metadata**\\n\\nI'm looking at the documentation regarding hash-based matching and upgrades. If there's a modification that doesn't match, I could try using --force, but I wouldn’t want to apply that on modified files. I want to establish what’s safe, like if the source root is workspace/skills and not classified as high-risk. I think I can get a sense of local modifications by checking for `.clawhub` metadata, and I’ll inspect installed skill directories, particularly for _meta.json files.\"}]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_HhZwJAXmum7YkKDIc3YtBlMw|fc_0b3ac7b405e714490169e433e10034819aac875ffb0ef5c269","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"set -e\nfor s in multi-search-engine context-memory-optimizer xiaohongshu-skill; do\n  d=\"$HOME/.openclaw/workspace/skills/$s\"\n  echo \"### $d\"\n  [ -d \"$d\" ] || continue\n  find \"$d\" -maxdepth 2 -type f | sed -n '1,80p'\n  echo\n done","workdir":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/coding-agent","timeout":30,"yieldMs":1000},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"set -e\\nfor s in multi-search-engine context-memory-optimizer xiaohongshu-skill; do\\n  d=\\\"$HOME/.openclaw/workspace/skills/$s\\\"\\n  echo \\\"### $d\\\"\\n  [ -d \\\"$d\\\" ] || continue\\n  find \\\"$d\\\" -maxdepth 2 -type f | sed -n '1,80p'\\n  echo\\n done\",\"workdir\":\"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/coding-agent\",\"timeout\":30,\"yieldMs\":1000}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_SXXMlKOxZ4Xbl8DjRRpXKbqV|fc_0b3ac7b405e714490169e433e10044819a821e3e167018f647","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"set -e\nfor s in skill-creator; do\n  for d in \"$HOME/Library/pnpm/global/5/.pnpm/openclaw@2026.4.10_@emnapi+core@1.9.2_@emnapi+runtime@1.9.2_@napi-rs+canvas@0.1.97_@typ_a90ffd2929abe8f398b8e8e6d84b8ef0/node_modules/openclaw/skills/$s\"; 